West European to World Science: Seventeenth–Twentieth Centuries -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex of Names and Places0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDeals with the intersection of issues associated with globalization and the dynamics of core-periphery relations. It places these debates in a large and vital context asking what the relations between cores and peripheries have in forming our vision of what constitutes globalization and what were and are its possible effects. In this sense the debate on globalization is framed as part of a larger and more crucial discourse that tries to account for the essential dynamics—economic, social, political and cultural—between metropolitan areas and their peripheries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aDependency. 0aGlobalization. 0aNeoliberalism. 0aRegional disparities. 0aRegional economics. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / International / Economics.2bisacsh  aEconomic history, Globalization, Nationalism, Neoliberalism, Regional disparities.1 aBalázs Szelényi, Reill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBatou, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerend, Ivan T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrenner, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChirot, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavid, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHobsbawm, Eric J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKocka, Jürgen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLove, Joseph L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRei